[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YashKumarVerma/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YashKumarVerma/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YashKumarVerma/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Explicitly disable layering check for TFLM bazel packages.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

[{"sha":"d236afda36626f3dd6dfea234413b3b4d62fc9a0","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding hooks in the Stream Executor API to get/set the AMDGPU gcnArchName device property","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/d236afda36626f3dd6dfea234413b3b4d62fc9a0"},{"sha":"ab9a9084d2feb820a1fe94e6d42825209eaed076","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Changing "GpuVersion" datatype to include hipDeviceProp_t::gcnArchName

Currently the "GpuVersion" datatype (for AMDGPU in XLA code) is an `int`, whose value is the same as the `int hipDeviceProp_t::gcnArch;` field.

Starting with ROCm 4.?, which introduces targetID support, that value will no longer be sufficient to create a LLVM AMDGPUTarget that accurately represents underlying GPU. We will need to information contained withing the `string hipDeviceProp_t gcnArchName` field for that purpose.

[{"sha":"5372045e1840fdb8dae5e00e770f766751c86512","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/terminal: Interrogate and initialize the terminal, if any

This is a helper package that creates a very thin abstraction over
terminal setup, with the main goal being to deal with all of the extra
setup we need to do in order to get a UTF-8-supporting virtual terminal
on a Windows system.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5372045e1840fdb8dae5e00e770f766751c86512"},{"sha":"d6b920ff84556db8b1c39bda5a696ffb67d8c9bf","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"main: initialize the terminal (if any) using internal/terminal

We need to call into terminal.Init in early startup to make sure that we
either have a suitable Terminal or that we disable attempts to use virtual
terminal escape sequences.

This commit gets the terminal initialized but doesn't do much with it
after that. Subsequent commits will make more use of this.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d6b920ff84556db8b1c39bda5a696ffb67d8c9bf"},{"sha":"7f63a84eb53e85654eefda53065cca42f41e02a0","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Use the new terminal.Streams object

Here we propagate in the initialized terminal.Streams from package main,
and then onwards to backends running in CLI mode.

This also replaces our use of helper/wrappedstreams to determine whether
stdin is a terminal or a pipe. helper/wrappedstreams returns incorrect
file descriptors on Windows, causing StdinPiped to always return false on
that platform and thus causing one of the odd behaviors discussed in
#18242.

Finally, this includes some wrappers around the ability to look up the
number of columns in the terminal in preparation for use elsewhere. These
wrappers deal with the fact that our unit tests typically won't populate
meta.Streams.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/7f63a84eb53e85654eefda53065cca42f41e02a0"},{"sha":"7b7a8c551dd656dbf74fb2456baf4dbdfc399f8c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend/local: Use terminal properties to tweak the plan output

We now require the output to accept UTF-8 and we can determine how wide
the terminal (if any) is, so here we begin to make use of that for the
"terraform plan" command.

The horizontal rule is now made of box drawing characters instead of
hyphens and fills the whole terminal width.

The paragraphs of text in the output are now also wrapped to fill the
terminal width, instead of the hard-wrapping we did before.

This is just a start down the road of making better use of the terminal
capabilities. Lots of other commands could benefit from updates like these
too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/7b7a8c551dd656dbf74fb2456baf4dbdfc399f8c"},{"sha":"5e1c0137264c242f37fc5450f32027e2eaa70dcb","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Use box drawing chars for rules in diagnostics

We were previously using some ASCII art to create some visual divisions
between parts of the diagnostic output. Now that we are requiring a UTF-8
terminal we can print out box drawing characters instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5e1c0137264c242f37fc5450f32027e2eaa70dcb"}]

Extending OpShardingProto/HloSharding to have a repeated OpMetadata field will allow for tracking the source(s) of a sharding when being assigned to an instruction or propagated. OpMetadata is reused to allow for flexibility and reuse of tracking of instructions (e.g. op name, op type, file and line, etc.). This only adds the field and updates the printer and parser to support the addition of this field.

For non tuple sharding, OpMetadata is added as an attribute to the sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={op_name="a"}}

Multiple metadata can be associated to a sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={{op_name="e"}, {op_name="f"}}}

Metadata on tuple sharding is unsupported in favor of metadata on tuple elements.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Change-Id: Id292f0512eeba335c34b8740f794f33b4b562ae9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/c62635d6633db1d1e633ecb4bb0daf352b775689"},{"sha":"c213508ff96af3d6b7dc51e349e6b02b48d5d85f","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite TpuExtractOutsideCompilation pass without assuming clustering.

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351405317
Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

values led to long integer values being presented in scientific

scientific notation and displays integer values as a sequence of digits

[{"sha":"febd380da9219e08ea493b5baff765e2ef2d99d5","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Do not hang in GPU tf.math.pow if RHS is a negative int.

Before, if the RHS to tf.math.pow in the GPU kernel was negative and the inputs were int64, the GPU kernel would hang. Eigen expects the RHS to be nonnegative and will go into an infinite loop otherwise. The CPU kernel already checks this and raises an error if the RHS is negative, but we cannot easily raise errors in GPU kernels.

OpMetadata is reused to allow for flexibility and reuse of tracking of instructions (e.g. op name, op type, file and line, etc.). This only adds the field and updates the printer and parser to support the addition of this field.

For non tuple sharding, OpMetadata is added as an attribute to the sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={op_name="a"}}

Multiple metadata can be associated to a sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={{op_name="e"}, {op_name="f"}}}

Metadata on tuple sharding is unsupported in favor of metadata on tuple elements.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old

Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Explicitly disable layering check for TFLM bazel packages.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Currently the "GpuVersion" datatype (for AMDGPU in XLA code) is an `int`, whose value is the same as the `int hipDeviceProp_t::gcnArch;` field.

Starting with ROCm 4.?, which introduces targetID support, that value will no longer be sufficient to create a LLVM AMDGPUTarget that accurately represents underlying GPU. We will need to information contained withing the `string hipDeviceProp_t gcnArchName` field for that purpose.

[{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"}]

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

the leyering_check disabled.

open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

make the internal and external builds consistent.

Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

[{"sha":"da555a2c9bdce45a944ff4c85a2981b79d763724","author":{"name":"Clement Courbet","email":"18a6ad33eeb00c3a39b33c2572bde72aa7e82ab1@google.com"},"message":"Optimize opencv dft by vectorizing radix2 and radix3.

This is useful for non power-of-two sizes when WITH_IPP is not an option.

This shows consistent improvement over openCV benchmarks, and we measure
even larger improvements on our internal workloads.

For example, for 320x480, `32FC*`, we can see a ~5% improvement}, as
`320=2^6*5` and `480=2^5*3*5`, so the improved radix3 version is used.
`64FC*` is flat as expected, as we do not specialize the functors for `double`
in this change.

A running GMainLoop processes many events on the GLib/GStreamer
world. While some things may work without it, many others wont.
Examples of these are signals, timers and many other source
events. The problem becomes more concerning by the fact that
some GStreamer elements rely on signals to work.

This commit allows the user to specify an OpenCV option to
start a main loop, if needed. Since the loop blocks, this is
done in a separate thread.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mpashchenkov/opencv/commits/e3da18121f836a3ef361a8f1847f6ae30d536770"},{"sha":"716450ceb569c62989ff67e3abf64da8357f414e","author":{"name":"Alexander Alekhin","email":"68add3c7f0912f500ebe6e9539930fd1bb229c72@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #18158 from legrosbuffle:3.4-vectorize-dft-radix","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mpashchenkov/opencv/commits/716450ceb569c62989ff67e3abf64da8357f414e"},{"sha":"099ad1a259f1f83af6da6826e78ebd645ee94004","author":{"name":"Dmitry Matveev","email":"2a4eea8e4cff9d49a31a783149ccd6400e8629ef@intel.com"},"message":"G-API: Desync -- fix the queue saturation problem

In this case, Copy won't read more data from a "last_written"
container than required, while feeding the desynchronized path.

Sometimes Copy don't get fused into an island and behaves
on its own -- in this case, it reads more data in advance
so the slow (desync) part actually processes some data in-sync
(more than actually [{"sha":"892bbc9797710e78cede18ba4baae3c4185ea2a9","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Explicitly disable layering check for TFLM bazel packages.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

See http://b/177257332 for more internal-only context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/892bbc9797710e78cede18ba4baae3c4185ea2a9"},{"sha":"49e4bbf895675b35011aa3aaa259481b5079718c","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"fix build formatting.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/49e4bbf895675b35011aa3aaa259481b5079718c"},{"sha":"989345b180c12c5f374f9ebdafd85e034618cae9","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46350 from advaitjain:fix-46347-layering-check

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wadezhan/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wadezhan/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wadezhan/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Extending OpShardingProto/HloSharding to have a repeated OpMetadata field will allow for tracking the source(s) of a sharding when being assigned to an instruction or propagated. OpMetadata is reused to allow for flexibility and reuse of tracking of instructions (e.g. op name, op type, file and line, etc.). This only adds the field and updates the printer and parser to support the addition of this field.

For non tuple sharding, OpMetadata is added as an attribute to the sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={op_name="a"}}

Multiple metadata can be associated to a sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={{op_name="e"}, {op_name="f"}}}

Metadata on tuple sharding is unsupported in favor of metadata on tuple elements.

* Lint rule to forbid access of cross-fork fields

We use a shared Fiber type for both reconciler forks (old and new). It
is a superset of all the fields used by both forks. However, there are
some fields that should only be used in the new fork, and others that
should only be used in the old fork.

Ideally we would enforce this with separate Flow types for each fork.
The problem is that the Fiber type is accessed by some packages outside
the reconciler (like React DOM), and get passed into the reconciler as
arguments. So there's no way to fork the Fiber type without also forking
the packages where they are used. FiberRoot has the same issue.

Instead, I've added a lint rule that forbids cross-fork access of
fork-specific fields. Fields that end in `_old` or `_new` are forbidden
from being used inside the new or old fork respectively. Or you can
specific custom fields using the ESLint plugin options.

I used this plugin to find and remove references to the effect list
in d2e914a.

* Mark effect list fields as old

And `subtreeTag` as new.

I didn't mark `lastEffect` because that name is also used by the
Hook type. Not super important; could rename to `lastEffect_old` but
idk if it's worth the effort.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/af219cc6e6c514099a667ffab4e2d80c5c0c1bcc"},{"sha":"c4e0768d7487a9359b74986e3b07841d2520f593","author":{"name":"inottn","email":"765a9a915b0c8b30b7d96c268531d508f6dcfc76@outlook.com"},"message":"Remove unused argument from `finishConcurrentRender` (#19689)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/c4e0768d7487a9359b74986e3b07841d2520f593"},{"sha":"5564f2c95bb61b446f93dc5c519740bdb39e1989","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Add React.startTransition (#19696)

* Remove distinction between long, short transitions

We're removing the `timeoutMs` option, so there's no longer any
distinction between "short" and "long" transitions. They're all treated
the same.

This commit doesn't remove `timeoutMs` yet, only combines the internal
priority levels.

* Disable `timeoutMs` argument

tl;dr
-----

- We're removing the `timeoutMs` argument from `useTransition`.
- Transitions will either immediately switch to a skeleton/placeholder
  view (when loading new content) or wait indefinitely until the data
  resolves (when refreshing stale content).
- This commit disables the `timeoutMS` so that the API has the desired
  semantics. It doesn't yet update the types or migrate all the test
  callers. I'll do those steps in follow-up PRs.

Motivation
----------

Currently, transitions initiated by `startTransition` / `useTransition`
accept a `timeoutMs` option. You can use this to control the maximum
amount of time that a transition is allowed to delay before we give up
and show a placeholder.

What we've discovered is that, in practice, every transition falls into
one of two categories: a **load** or a **refresh**:

- **Loading a new screen**: show the next screen as soon as possible,
  even if the data hasn't finished loading. Use a skeleton/placeholder
  UI to show progress.
- **Refreshing a screen that's already visible**: keep showing the
  current screen indefinitely, for as long as it takes to load the fresh
  data, even if the current data is stale. Use a pending state (and
  maybe a busy indicator) to show progress.

In other words, transitions should either *delay indefinitely* (for a
refresh) or they should show a placeholder *instantly* (for a load).
There's not much use for transitions that are delayed for a
small-but-noticeable amount of time.

So, the plan is to remove the `timeoutMs` option. Instead, we'll assign
an effective timeout of `0` for loads, and `Infinity` for refreshes.

The mechanism for distinguishing a load from a refresh already exists in
the current model. If a component suspends, and the nearest Suspense
boundary hasn't already mounted, we treat that as a load, because
there's nothing on the screen. However, if the nearest boundary is
mounted, we treat that as a refresh, since it's already showing content.

If you need to fix a transition to be treated as a load instead of a
refresh, or vice versa, the solution will involve rearranging the
location of your Suspense boundaries. It may also involve adding a key.

We're still working on proper documentation for these patterns. In the
meantime, please reach out to us if you run into problems that you're
unsure how to fix.

We will remove `timeoutMs` from `useDeferredValue`, too, and apply the
same load versus refresh semantics to the update that spawns the
deferred value.

Note that there are other types of delays that are not related to
transitions; for example, we will still throttle the appearance of
nested placeholders (we refer to this as the placeholder "train model"),
and we may still apply a Just Noticeable Difference heuristic (JND) in
some cases. These aren't going anywhere. (Well, the JND heuristic might
but for different reasons than those discussed above.)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/8da0da0937af154b775b243c9d28b6aa50db696b"},{"sha":"1eaafc9ade46ba708b2361b324dd907d019e3939","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Clean up timeoutMs-related implementation details (#19704)

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

[{"sha":"db751a1389b9f0ffab128d958891354d6e579be7","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/db751a1389b9f0ffab128d958891354d6e579be7"}]

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

The caching of the LSP client that is rooted in project2MimeType2Server
does not work. In the WeakHashMap the keys are help by weak references
and the key is invalidated, once it is GCed. The URIs that are used
as keys become immediately eligible for GC and thus the cache is not
used at all.

To fix this, use a regular HashMap with WeakReference values.

The LSP Clients themselves are either strongly referenced from other
components or can be collected. To not create excessive start/stops of
servers, an additional strong reference is retained for a certain time
after the last bind request was issued. Only after the timeout has
occured, that extra reference is released and the bindings could become
eligible for GC.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hectorespert/netbeans/commits/ebde2a5904506dc10a035e8e4ef9adbc80889b02"},{"sha":"b6104f59cea7350169f9d0737350bc71225b1e6c","author":{"name":"Dusan Balek","email":"93d74d1cc9df89834360f8b313cef058ebced495@oracle.com"},"message":"Existing CodeGenerators exposed as CodeActions via LSP. values led to long integer values being presented in scientific
notation (e.g. 1.2345678e+07). While technically correct, this is an

scientific notation and displays integer values as a sequence of digits

Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

* Lint rule to forbid access of cross-fork fields

We use a shared Fiber type for both reconciler forks (old and new). It
is a superset of all the fields used by both forks. However, there are
some fields that should only be used in the new fork, and others that
should only be used in the old fork.

Ideally we would enforce this with separate Flow types for each fork.
The problem is that the Fiber type is accessed by some packages outside
the reconciler (like React DOM), and get passed into the reconciler as
arguments. So there's no way to fork the Fiber type without also forking
the packages where they are used. FiberRoot has the same issue.

Instead, I've added a lint rule that forbids cross-fork access of
fork-specific fields. Fields that end in `_old` or `_new` are forbidden
from being used inside the new or old fork respectively. Or you can
specific custom fields using the ESLint plugin options.

I used this plugin to find and remove references to the effect list
in d2e914a.

* Mark effect list fields as old

And `subtreeTag` as new.

I didn't mark `lastEffect` because that name is also used by the
Hook type. Not super important; could rename to `lastEffect_old` but

* Remove distinction between long, short transitions

We're removing the `timeoutMs` option, so there's no longer any
distinction between "short" and "long" transitions. They're all treated
the same.

This commit doesn't remove `timeoutMs` yet, only combines the internal
priority levels.

* Disable `timeoutMs` argument

tl;dr
-----

- We're removing the `timeoutMs` argument from `useTransition`.
- Transitions will either immediately switch to a skeleton/placeholder
  view (when loading new content) or wait indefinitely until the data
  resolves (when refreshing stale content).
- This commit disables the `timeoutMS` so that the API has the desired
  semantics. It doesn't yet update the types or migrate all the test
  callers. I'll do those steps in follow-up PRs.

Motivation
----------

Currently, transitions initiated by `startTransition` / `useTransition`
accept a `timeoutMs` option. You can use this to control the maximum
amount of time that a transition is allowed to delay before we give up
and show a placeholder.

What we've discovered is that, in practice, every transition falls into
one of two categories: a **load** or a **refresh**:

- **Loading a new screen**: show the next screen as soon as possible,
  even if the data hasn't finished loading. Use a skeleton/placeholder
  UI to show progress.
- **Refreshing a screen that's already visible**: keep showing the
  current screen indefinitely, for as long as it takes to load the fresh
  data, even if the current data is stale. Use a pending state (and
  maybe a busy indicator) to show progress.

In other words, transitions should either *delay indefinitely* (for a
refresh) or they should show a placeholder *instantly* (for a load).
There's not much use for transitions that are delayed for a
small-but-noticeable amount of time.

So, the plan is to remove the `timeoutMs` option. Instead, we'll assign
an effective timeout of `0` for loads, and `Infinity` for refreshes.

The mechanism for distinguishing a load from a refresh already exists in
the current model. If a component suspends, and the nearest Suspense
boundary hasn't already mounted, we treat that as a load, because
there's nothing on the screen. However, if the nearest boundary is
mounted, we treat that as a refresh, since it's already showing content.

If you need to fix a transition to be treated as a load instead of a
refresh, or vice versa, the solution will involve rearranging the
location of your Suspense boundaries. It may also involve adding a key.

We're still working on proper documentation for these patterns. In the
meantime, please reach out to us if you run into problems that you're
unsure how to fix.

We will remove `timeoutMs` from `useDeferredValue`, too, and apply the
same load versus refresh semantics to the update that spawns the
deferred value.

Note that there are other types of delays that are not related to
transitions; for example, we will still throttle the appearance of
nested placeholders (we refer to this as the placeholder "train model"),
and we may still apply a Just Noticeable Difference heuristic (JND) in
some cases. These aren't going anywhere. (Well, the JND heuristic might
but for different reasons than those discussed above.)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/8da0da0937af154b775b243c9d28b6aa50db696b"},{"sha":"1eaafc9ade46ba708b2361b324dd907d019e3939","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Clean up timeoutMs-related implementation details (#19704)

[{"sha":"32f79ece532cbf639c614ad67dc3d5f6f6db83c9","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"backend/local: Use terminal properties to tweak the plan output

We now require the output to accept UTF-8 and we can determine how wide
the terminal (if any) is, so here we begin to make use of that for the
"terraform plan" command.

The horizontal rule is now made of box drawing characters instead of
hyphens and fills the whole terminal width.

The paragraphs of text in the output are now also wrapped to fill the
terminal width, instead of the hard-wrapping we did before.

This is just a start down the road of making better use of the terminal
capabilities. Lots of other commands could benefit from updates like these
too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/32f79ece532cbf639c614ad67dc3d5f6f6db83c9"},{"sha":"4f2c0ab3a2d6d180eab114911b9edcbf888a8957","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/format: Use box drawing chars for rules in diagnostics

We were previously using some ASCII art to create some visual divisions
between parts of the diagnostic output. Now that we are requiring a UTF-8
terminal we can print out box drawing characters instead.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f2c0ab3a2d6d180eab114911b9edcbf888a8957"}]

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"}]

* Lint rule to forbid access of cross-fork fields

We use a shared Fiber type for both reconciler forks (old and new). It
is a superset of all the fields used by both forks. However, there are
some fields that should only be used in the new fork, and others that
should only be used in the old fork.

Ideally we would enforce this with separate Flow types for each fork.
The problem is that the Fiber type is accessed by some packages outside
the reconciler (like React DOM), and get passed into the reconciler as
arguments. So there's no way to fork the Fiber type without also forking
the packages where they are used. FiberRoot has the same issue.

Instead, I've added a lint rule that forbids cross-fork access of
fork-specific fields. Fields that end in `_old` or `_new` are forbidden
from being used inside the new or old fork respectively. Or you can
specific custom fields using the ESLint plugin options.

I used this plugin to find and remove references to the effect list
in d2e914a.

* Mark effect list fields as old

And `subtreeTag` as new.

I didn't mark `lastEffect` because that name is also used by the
Hook type. Not super important; could rename to `lastEffect_old` but
idk if it's worth the effort.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/af219cc6e6c514099a667ffab4e2d80c5c0c1bcc"},{"sha":"c4e0768d7487a9359b74986e3b07841d2520f593","author":{"name":"inottn","email":"765a9a915b0c8b30b7d96c268531d508f6dcfc76@outlook.com"},"message":"Remove unused argument from `finishConcurrentRender` (#19689)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/c4e0768d7487a9359b74986e3b07841d2520f593"},{"sha":"5564f2c95bb61b446f93dc5c519740bdb39e1989","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Add React.startTransition (#19696)

* Remove distinction between long, short transitions

We're removing the `timeoutMs` option, so there's no longer any
distinction between "short" and "long" transitions. They're all treated
the same.

This commit doesn't remove `timeoutMs` yet, only combines the internal
priority levels.

* Disable `timeoutMs` argument

tl;dr
-----

- We're removing the `timeoutMs` argument from `useTransition`.
- Transitions will either immediately switch to a skeleton/placeholder
  view (when loading new content) or wait indefinitely until the data
  resolves (when refreshing stale content).
- This commit disables the `timeoutMS` so that the API has the desired
  semantics. It doesn't yet update the types or migrate all the test
  callers. I'll do those steps in follow-up PRs.

Motivation
----------

Currently, transitions initiated by `startTransition` / `useTransition`
accept a `timeoutMs` option. You can use this to control the maximum
amount of time that a transition is allowed to delay before we give up
and show a placeholder.

What we've discovered is that, in practice, every transition falls into
one of two categories: a **load** or a **refresh**:

- **Loading a new screen**: show the next screen as soon as possible,
  even if the data hasn't finished loading. Use a skeleton/placeholder
  UI to show progress.
- **Refreshing a screen that's already visible**: keep showing the
  current screen indefinitely, for as long as it takes to load the fresh
  data, even if the current data is stale. Use a pending state (and
  maybe a busy indicator) to show progress.

In other words, transitions should either *delay indefinitely* (for a
refresh) or they should show a placeholder *instantly* (for a load).
There's not much use for transitions that are delayed for a
small-but-noticeable amount of time.

So, the plan is to remove the `timeoutMs` option. Instead, we'll assign
an effective timeout of `0` for loads, and `Infinity` for refreshes.

The mechanism for distinguishing a load from a refresh already exists in
the current model. If a component suspends, and the nearest Suspense
boundary hasn't already mounted, we treat that as a load, because
there's nothing on the screen. However, if the nearest boundary is
mounted, we treat that as a refresh, since it's already showing content.

If you need to fix a transition to be treated as a load instead of a
refresh, or vice versa, the solution will involve rearranging the
location of your Suspense boundaries. It may also involve adding a key.

We're still working on proper documentation for these patterns. In the
meantime, please reach out to us if you run into problems that you're
unsure how to fix.

We will remove `timeoutMs` from `useDeferredValue`, too, and apply the
same load versus refresh semantics to the update that spawns the
deferred value.

Note that there are other types of delays that are not related to
transitions; for example, we will still throttle the appearance of
nested placeholders (we refer to this as the placeholder "train model"),
and we may still apply a Just Noticeable Difference heuristic (JND) in
some cases. These aren't going anywhere. (Well, the JND heuristic might
but for different reasons than those discussed above.)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/8da0da0937af154b775b243c9d28b6aa50db696b"},{"sha":"1eaafc9ade46ba708b2361b324dd907d019e3939","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Clean up timeoutMs-related implementation details (#19704)

[{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JCofman/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JCofman/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"}]

* Failing test for #19608

* Attach Listeners Eagerly to Roots and Portal Containers

* Forbid createEventHandle with custom events

We can't support this without adding more complexity. It's not clear that this is even desirable, as none of our existing use cases need custom events. This API primarily exists as a deprecation strategy for Flare, so I don't think it is important to expand its support beyond what Flare replacement code currently needs. * Lint rule to forbid access of cross-fork fields

We use a shared Fiber type for both reconciler forks (old and new). It
is a superset of all the fields used by both forks. However, there are
some fields that should only be used in the new fork, and others that
should only be used in the old fork.

Ideally we would enforce this with separate Flow types for each fork.
The problem is that the Fiber type is accessed by some packages outside
the reconciler (like React DOM), and get passed into the reconciler as
arguments. So there's no way to fork the Fiber type without also forking
the packages where they are used. FiberRoot has the same issue.

Instead, I've added a lint rule that forbids cross-fork access of
fork-specific fields. Fields that end in `_old` or `_new` are forbidden
from being used inside the new or old fork respectively. Or you can
specific custom fields using the ESLint plugin options.

I used this plugin to find and remove references to the effect list
in d2e914a.

* Mark effect list fields as old

And `subtreeTag` as new.

I didn't mark `lastEffect` because that name is also used by the
Hook type. Not super important; could rename to `lastEffect_old` but

* Remove distinction between long, short transitions

We're removing the `timeoutMs` option, so there's no longer any
distinction between "short" and "long" transitions. They're all treated
the same.

This commit doesn't remove `timeoutMs` yet, only combines the internal
priority levels.

* Disable `timeoutMs` argument

tl;dr
-----

- We're removing the `timeoutMs` argument from `useTransition`.
- Transitions will either immediately switch to a skeleton/placeholder
  view (when loading new content) or wait indefinitely until the data
  resolves (when refreshing stale content).
- This commit disables the `timeoutMS` so that the API has the desired
  semantics. It doesn't yet update the types or migrate all the test
  callers. I'll do those steps in follow-up PRs.

Motivation
----------

Currently, transitions initiated by `startTransition` / `useTransition`
accept a `timeoutMs` option. You can use this to control the maximum
amount of time that a transition is allowed to delay before we give up
and show a placeholder.

What we've discovered is that, in practice, every transition falls into
one of two categories: a **load** or a **refresh**:

- **Loading a new screen**: show the next screen as soon as possible,
  even if the data hasn't finished loading. Use a skeleton/placeholder
  UI to show progress.
- **Refreshing a screen that's already visible**: keep showing the
  current screen indefinitely, for as long as it takes to load the fresh
  data, even if the current data is stale. Use a pending state (and
  maybe a busy indicator) to show progress.

In other words, transitions should either *delay indefinitely* (for a
refresh) or they should show a placeholder *instantly* (for a load).
There's not much use for transitions that are delayed for a
small-but-noticeable amount of time.

So, the plan is to remove the `timeoutMs` option. Instead, we'll assign
an effective timeout of `0` for loads, and `Infinity` for refreshes.

The mechanism for distinguishing a load from a refresh already exists in
the current model. If a component suspends, and the nearest Suspense
boundary hasn't already mounted, we treat that as a load, because
there's nothing on the screen. However, if the nearest boundary is
mounted, we treat that as a refresh, since it's already showing content.

If you need to fix a transition to be treated as a load instead of a
refresh, or vice versa, the solution will involve rearranging the
location of your Suspense boundaries. It may also involve adding a key.

We're still working on proper documentation for these patterns. In the
meantime, please reach out to us if you run into problems that you're
unsure how to fix.

We will remove `timeoutMs` from `useDeferredValue`, too, and apply the
same load versus refresh semantics to the update that spawns the
deferred value.

Note that there are other types of delays that are not related to
transitions; for example, we will still throttle the appearance of
nested placeholders (we refer to this as the placeholder "train model"),
and we may still apply a Just Noticeable Difference heuristic (JND) in
some cases. These aren't going anywhere. (Well, the JND heuristic might
but for different reasons than those discussed above.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/8da0da0937af154b775b243c9d28b6aa50db696b"},{"sha":"1eaafc9ade46ba708b2361b324dd907d019e3939","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Clean up timeoutMs-related implementation details (#19704)

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 347714345
Change-Id: Ide35f47bc00e2a1bf8a57dab6f538b48105c235f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/andrewstevens-infineon/tensorflow/commits/062d6bdc2d48673c3781008e56a945bb2e17dad9"},{"sha":"301cc63204f67ba1f62bf511a5291deda23de8d5","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Speed up tf-tpu-outside-compilation-cluster pass by not processing dependent ops multiple times

Currently, this uses stack to maintain the op worklist using SetVector which will cause some ops to be visited multiple times as the ops are not necessarily popped in the topological order. This will have exponential complexity.

Visited ops are now tracked exclusively to make it linear time. Added a TODO to use GraphCycle data structure that should help further improve the performance.

At least for function placement this matches the behavior of un-inlined PartitionedCallOp (default_device to placer only affects nodes without a requested placement).

For functional cond (and presumably while) the un-inlined behavior appears to be single-device-only, so this change causes behavior to diverge there (it already diverged somewhat in allowing multi-device body graphs at all).

Fixes #44011.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kalecio/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kalecio/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kalecio/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Jeffkeen7/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Jeffkeen7/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"}]

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.
