information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"},{"sha":"d380f5873c5ba09b99860fba061200a6e27b3aaa","author":{"name":"Paul Thrasher","email":"d943e3484fefc8c5080ef9d8c0757459e55f3371@hashicorp.com"},"message":"Allow runs to continue on tfce error

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"1a324f5c7249fbff56ed0b488d3cb20379a35d92","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Allow more of the internal checks to have open-source counterparts.

 * assert can not be used (static_assert is ok).

Manually tested by adding the disallowed strings to the code and

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Currently the "GpuVersion" datatype (for AMDGPU in XLA code) is an `int`, whose value is the same as the `int hipDeviceProp_t::gcnArch;` field.

Starting with ROCm 4.?, which introduces targetID support, that value will no longer be sufficient to create a LLVM AMDGPUTarget that accurately represents underlying GPU. We will need to information contained withing the `string hipDeviceProp_t gcnArchName` field for that purpose.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Extending OpShardingProto/HloSharding to have a repeated OpMetadata field will allow for tracking the source(s) of a sharding when being assigned to an instruction or propagated. OpMetadata is reused to allow for flexibility and reuse of tracking of instructions (e.g. op name, op type, file and line, etc.). This only adds the field and updates the printer and parser to support the addition of this field.

For non tuple sharding, OpMetadata is added as an attribute to the sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={op_name="a"}}

Multiple metadata can be associated to a sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={{op_name="e"}, {op_name="f"}}}

Metadata on tuple sharding is unsupported in favor of metadata on tuple elements.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"}]

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"1a324f5c7249fbff56ed0b488d3cb20379a35d92","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Allow more of the internal checks to have open-source counterparts.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

See http://b/177257332 for more internal-only context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/892bbc9797710e78cede18ba4baae3c4185ea2a9"},{"sha":"49e4bbf895675b35011aa3aaa259481b5079718c","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"fix build formatting.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/49e4bbf895675b35011aa3aaa259481b5079718c"},{"sha":"abcabe12666d064da4710d965c36a59c937eab12","author":{"name":"A. This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

Extending OpShardingProto/HloSharding to have a repeated OpMetadata field will allow for tracking the source(s) of a sharding when being assigned to an instruction or propagated. OpMetadata is reused to allow for flexibility and reuse of tracking of instructions (e.g. op name, op type, file and line, etc.). This only adds the field and updates the printer and parser to support the addition of this field.

For non tuple sharding, OpMetadata is added as an attribute to the sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={op_name="a"}}

Multiple metadata can be associated to a sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={{op_name="e"}, {op_name="f"}}}

Metadata on tuple sharding is unsupported in favor of metadata on tuple elements.

[{"sha":"dd5bbd57dd334bb91bb67688020be539f8290fda","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite TpuExtractOutsideCompilation pass without assuming clustering.

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351405317
Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

[{"sha":"e973623daa139e93d94840e3c09aedb6fc1e0c90","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/e973623daa139e93d94840e3c09aedb6fc1e0c90"},{"sha":"a448873438b31e12370ddcfd9af06e311a4bbe2c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/a448873438b31e12370ddcfd9af06e311a4bbe2c"}]

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

Core was previously ignoring JSON-encoded dynamic values, but these are
technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.
Since we already have the decoder for Json state, it's minimal effort to
support this on all plugin methods too.

This change also gives providers an easy way to implement the
UpgradeResourceState method. The obvious implementation of returning the same
JSON-encoded value has tripped up a few providers not using the legacy
SDK already, and we should have at least indicated that the value was
being lost.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e"},{"sha":"98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26606 from hashicorp/jbardin/proposed-set-comparison

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"}]

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Currently the "GpuVersion" datatype (for AMDGPU in XLA code) is an `int`, whose value is the same as the `int hipDeviceProp_t::gcnArch;` field.

Starting with ROCm 4.?, which introduces targetID support, that value will no longer be sufficient to create a LLVM AMDGPUTarget that accurately represents underlying GPU. We will need to information contained withing the `string hipDeviceProp_t gcnArchName` field for that purpose.

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old

`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

Currently, model.fit(class_weight={}) only works if y_data is of
rank 2 in the output, e.g. (batch_size,) or (batch_size, N_one_hot)
(if N==1, squeeze).

This change adds a flag `class_weight_mode`="multi_dim" to
`model.compile()` that allows dense label  representations of
any shape to be compatible with `class_weight` in `model.fit()`
e.g. image or temporal / sequence data. The relevant tests are
included for the DataHandler.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least

Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"}]

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JackEasons/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"}]

Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Explicitly disable layering check for TFLM bazel packages.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op FILL. There is an annoying difference between internal
and external versions of the code that causes clang-formatting
errors in CI checks (see issue #46297). When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/0a342ee36b2627c2ce5d3d1bb4103191dd8d7711"},{"sha":"1a324f5c7249fbff56ed0b488d3cb20379a35d92","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Allow more of the internal checks to have open-source counterparts.

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

We don't have a separate codepath to handle the internals of
AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat
empty strings as null strings within set objects to avoid the failed

[{"sha":"ca84950776662430f432f4d655568d3ad032bfc8","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/ca84950776662430f432f4d655568d3ad032bfc8"}]

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Change-Id: Id292f0512eeba335c34b8740f794f33b4b562ae9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/c62635d6633db1d1e633ecb4bb0daf352b775689"},{"sha":"c213508ff96af3d6b7dc51e349e6b02b48d5d85f","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite TpuExtractOutsideCompilation pass without assuming clustering.

This pass is now handled by first:
1. Decomposing control flow into the host and device portions first.
2. Moving all outside compilation ops to run in a single host parallel_execute region.

This simplifies the flow greatly and leads to simpler code path.  It will also allow the use of tf_device::LaunchOp to represent outside compilation regions.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351405317
Change-Id: I6b15e35f92f52279403142d556c481b92c0dd40d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/0e43a67584000bf60c333e2b0bf024ba91d60010"},{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

[{"sha":"253111e23b612585e61f28acaf1b6dd6a965249b","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Stop holding custom devices in TensorHandles

My hope is to not change the custom device API much, just clean up the implementation.

Previously TensorHandles held Tensors which held the void* custom device tensor handle data. This required a bunch of special cases, mostly because the TensorHandle's device wasn't a physical device.

Now EagerOperations still accept custom device TensorHandles, but deal with them before execution (either by copying them off the custom device or by executing the operation on a custom device). This means the rest of the runtime can assume TensorHandles are on physical devices, and gives custom device tensor handles some freedom to evolve.

Rolling cl/350684489 forward with a fix for making packed tensors from custom device tensors. This requires one new custom device method to maintain the previous (accidental) functionality.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

We don't have a separate codepath to handle the internals of
AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Change-Id: Ide35f47bc00e2a1bf8a57dab6f538b48105c235f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ausaafnabi/tensorflow/commits/062d6bdc2d48673c3781008e56a945bb2e17dad9"},{"sha":"301cc63204f67ba1f62bf511a5291deda23de8d5","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Speed up tf-tpu-outside-compilation-cluster pass by not processing dependent ops multiple times

Currently, this uses stack to maintain the op worklist using SetVector which will cause some ops to be visited multiple times as the ops are not necessarily popped in the topological order. This will have exponential complexity.

Visited ops are now tracked exclusively to make it linear time. Added a TODO to use GraphCycle data structure that should help further improve the performance.

At least for function placement this matches the behavior of un-inlined PartitionedCallOp (default_device to placer only affects nodes without a requested placement).

Fixes #44011.

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

[{"sha":"d236afda36626f3dd6dfea234413b3b4d62fc9a0","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding hooks in the Stream Executor API to get/set the AMDGPU gcnArchName device property","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/d236afda36626f3dd6dfea234413b3b4d62fc9a0"},{"sha":"ab9a9084d2feb820a1fe94e6d42825209eaed076","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Changing "GpuVersion" datatype to include hipDeviceProp_t::gcnArchName

Currently the "GpuVersion" datatype (for AMDGPU in XLA code) is an `int`, whose value is the same as the `int hipDeviceProp_t::gcnArch;` field.

Starting with ROCm 4.?, which introduces targetID support, that value will no longer be sufficient to create a LLVM AMDGPUTarget that accurately represents underlying GPU. We will need to information contained withing the `string hipDeviceProp_t gcnArchName` field for that purpose.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Change-Id: Idfa6fe5a01969efb888cc9a22718e72d881f1835","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/96fdbb1a8dcc2f32ec108812245e70ed12ca1748"},{"sha":"7618f357a8ed31108d9cfa9909b5ae6ce0559653","author":{"name":"Marcello Maggioni","email":"7285fa981f1029f5dce86f0c3ffbaf175806dbc8@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Adding support for detecting potential parallel dimensions in gather.

Some gathers have indices driven by IOTAs that cause the access to be
partitionable in the dimension indexed by the dimension with of the IOTA.
An example is:

  %iota.1 = iota()
  %indices = concatenate(..., %iota.1, ...)
  ... = gather(..., %indices)

which is a pattern followed by tf.reverse_sequence for example.

This patch adds support to detecting such situation and allowing sharding
of the gather across devices.

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lancygoyal/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Extending OpShardingProto/HloSharding to have a repeated OpMetadata field will allow for tracking the source(s) of a sharding when being assigned to an instruction or propagated. OpMetadata is reused to allow for flexibility and reuse of tracking of instructions (e.g. op name, op type, file and line, etc.). This only adds the field and updates the printer and parser to support the addition of this field.

For non tuple sharding, OpMetadata is added as an attribute to the sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={op_name="a"}}

Multiple metadata can be associated to a sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={{op_name="e"}, {op_name="f"}}}

Metadata on tuple sharding is unsupported in favor of metadata on tuple elements.

Note that we will need to manually ensure that any new bazel package has
the leyering_check disabled.

The internal builds have layering_check turned on by default, while the
open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

However, turning it on (with `layering_check` instead of
`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

```
bazel build tensorflow/lite/micro/kernels:add_test --repo_env=CC=`which clang`
```

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

As a result, we are currently turning off the layering_check to at least
make the internal and external builds consistent.

Fixes #46347

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"}]

open-source builds have them turned off by default. Ideally, we would
explicitly turn them on for the open-source build.

`-layering_check`) and building with this command:

results in a number of additional build errors that will need much
broader changes to the TFLM BUILD files to fix.

make the internal and external builds consistent.

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351283702
Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

* Lint rule to forbid access of cross-fork fields

We use a shared Fiber type for both reconciler forks (old and new). It
is a superset of all the fields used by both forks. However, there are
some fields that should only be used in the new fork, and others that
should only be used in the old fork.

Ideally we would enforce this with separate Flow types for each fork.
The problem is that the Fiber type is accessed by some packages outside
the reconciler (like React DOM), and get passed into the reconciler as
arguments. So there's no way to fork the Fiber type without also forking
the packages where they are used. FiberRoot has the same issue.

Instead, I've added a lint rule that forbids cross-fork access of
fork-specific fields. Fields that end in `_old` or `_new` are forbidden
from being used inside the new or old fork respectively. Or you can
specific custom fields using the ESLint plugin options.

I used this plugin to find and remove references to the effect list
in d2e914a.

* Mark effect list fields as old

And `subtreeTag` as new.

I didn't mark `lastEffect` because that name is also used by the
Hook type. Not super important; could rename to `lastEffect_old` but
idk if it's worth the effort.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/af219cc6e6c514099a667ffab4e2d80c5c0c1bcc"},{"sha":"c4e0768d7487a9359b74986e3b07841d2520f593","author":{"name":"inottn","email":"765a9a915b0c8b30b7d96c268531d508f6dcfc76@outlook.com"},"message":"Remove unused argument from `finishConcurrentRender` (#19689)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/c4e0768d7487a9359b74986e3b07841d2520f593"},{"sha":"5564f2c95bb61b446f93dc5c519740bdb39e1989","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Add React.startTransition (#19696)

tl;dr
-----

- We're removing the `timeoutMs` argument from `useTransition`.
- Transitions will either immediately switch to a skeleton/placeholder
  view (when loading new content) or wait indefinitely until the data
  resolves (when refreshing stale content).
- This commit disables the `timeoutMS` so that the API has the desired
  semantics. It doesn't yet update the types or migrate all the test
  callers. I'll do those steps in follow-up PRs.

Motivation
----------

Currently, transitions initiated by `startTransition` / `useTransition`
accept a `timeoutMs` option. You can use this to control the maximum
amount of time that a transition is allowed to delay before we give up
and show a placeholder.

What we've discovered is that, in practice, every transition falls into
one of two categories: a **load** or a **refresh**:

- **Loading a new screen**: show the next screen as soon as possible,
  even if the data hasn't finished loading. Use a skeleton/placeholder
  UI to show progress.
- **Refreshing a screen that's already visible**: keep showing the
  current screen indefinitely, for as long as it takes to load the fresh
  data, even if the current data is stale. Use a pending state (and
  maybe a busy indicator) to show progress.

In other words, transitions should either *delay indefinitely* (for a
refresh) or they should show a placeholder *instantly* (for a load).
There's not much use for transitions that are delayed for a
small-but-noticeable amount of time.

So, the plan is to remove the `timeoutMs` option. Instead, we'll assign
an effective timeout of `0` for loads, and `Infinity` for refreshes.

The mechanism for distinguishing a load from a refresh already exists in
the current model. If a component suspends, and the nearest Suspense
boundary hasn't already mounted, we treat that as a load, because
there's nothing on the screen. However, if the nearest boundary is
mounted, we treat that as a refresh, since it's already showing content.

If you need to fix a transition to be treated as a load instead of a
refresh, or vice versa, the solution will involve rearranging the
location of your Suspense boundaries. It may also involve adding a key.

We're still working on proper documentation for these patterns. In the
meantime, please reach out to us if you run into problems that you're
unsure how to fix.

We will remove `timeoutMs` from `useDeferredValue`, too, and apply the
same load versus refresh semantics to the update that spawns the
deferred value.

Note that there are other types of delays that are not related to
transitions; for example, we will still throttle the appearance of
nested placeholders (we refer to this as the placeholder "train model"),
and we may still apply a Just Noticeable Difference heuristic (JND) in
some cases. These aren't going anywhere. (Well, the JND heuristic might

* Lint rule to forbid access of cross-fork fields

We use a shared Fiber type for both reconciler forks (old and new). It
is a superset of all the fields used by both forks. However, there are
some fields that should only be used in the new fork, and others that
should only be used in the old fork.

Ideally we would enforce this with separate Flow types for each fork.
The problem is that the Fiber type is accessed by some packages outside
the reconciler (like React DOM), and get passed into the reconciler as
arguments. So there's no way to fork the Fiber type without also forking
the packages where they are used. FiberRoot has the same issue.

Instead, I've added a lint rule that forbids cross-fork access of
fork-specific fields. Fields that end in `_old` or `_new` are forbidden
from being used inside the new or old fork respectively. Or you can
specific custom fields using the ESLint plugin options.

I used this plugin to find and remove references to the effect list
in d2e914a.

* Mark effect list fields as old

And `subtreeTag` as new.

I didn't mark `lastEffect` because that name is also used by the
Hook type. Not super important; could rename to `lastEffect_old` but

* Remove distinction between long, short transitions

We're removing the `timeoutMs` option, so there's no longer any
distinction between "short" and "long" transitions. They're all treated
the same.

This commit doesn't remove `timeoutMs` yet, only combines the internal
priority levels.

* Disable `timeoutMs` argument

tl;dr
-----

- We're removing the `timeoutMs` argument from `useTransition`.
- Transitions will either immediately switch to a skeleton/placeholder
  view (when loading new content) or wait indefinitely until the data
  resolves (when refreshing stale content).
- This commit disables the `timeoutMS` so that the API has the desired
  semantics. It doesn't yet update the types or migrate all the test
  callers. I'll do those steps in follow-up PRs.

Motivation
----------

Currently, transitions initiated by `startTransition` / `useTransition`
accept a `timeoutMs` option. You can use this to control the maximum
amount of time that a transition is allowed to delay before we give up
and show a placeholder.

What we've discovered is that, in practice, every transition falls into
one of two categories: a **load** or a **refresh**:

- **Loading a new screen**: show the next screen as soon as possible,
  even if the data hasn't finished loading. Use a skeleton/placeholder
  UI to show progress.
- **Refreshing a screen that's already visible**: keep showing the
  current screen indefinitely, for as long as it takes to load the fresh
  data, even if the current data is stale. Use a pending state (and
  maybe a busy indicator) to show progress.

In other words, transitions should either *delay indefinitely* (for a
refresh) or they should show a placeholder *instantly* (for a load).
There's not much use for transitions that are delayed for a
small-but-noticeable amount of time.

So, the plan is to remove the `timeoutMs` option. Instead, we'll assign
an effective timeout of `0` for loads, and `Infinity` for refreshes.

The mechanism for distinguishing a load from a refresh already exists in
the current model. If a component suspends, and the nearest Suspense
boundary hasn't already mounted, we treat that as a load, because
there's nothing on the screen. However, if the nearest boundary is
mounted, we treat that as a refresh, since it's already showing content.

If you need to fix a transition to be treated as a load instead of a
refresh, or vice versa, the solution will involve rearranging the
location of your Suspense boundaries. It may also involve adding a key.

We're still working on proper documentation for these patterns. In the
meantime, please reach out to us if you run into problems that you're
unsure how to fix.

We will remove `timeoutMs` from `useDeferredValue`, too, and apply the
same load versus refresh semantics to the update that spawns the
deferred value.

Note that there are other types of delays that are not related to
transitions; for example, we will still throttle the appearance of
nested placeholders (we refer to this as the placeholder "train model"),
and we may still apply a Just Noticeable Difference heuristic (JND) in
some cases. These aren't going anywhere. (Well, the JND heuristic might
but for different reasons than those discussed above.)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mertxe78/react/commits/8da0da0937af154b775b243c9d28b6aa50db696b"},{"sha":"1eaafc9ade46ba708b2361b324dd907d019e3939","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Clean up timeoutMs-related implementation details (#19704)

[{"sha":"6a1b5968b63a5ec94f1816ec855a996508f97959","author":{"name":"Andy Ly","email":"ee92f4a5326670b7718293ef87adfe1573316ab0@google.com"},"message":"Add OpMetadata list to OpShardingProto/HloSharding.

Extending OpShardingProto/HloSharding to have a repeated OpMetadata field will allow for tracking the source(s) of a sharding when being assigned to an instruction or propagated. OpMetadata is reused to allow for flexibility and reuse of tracking of instructions (e.g. op name, op type, file and line, etc.). This only adds the field and updates the printer and parser to support the addition of this field.

For non tuple sharding, OpMetadata is added as an attribute to the sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={op_name="a"}}

Multiple metadata can be associated to a sharding
e.g.
{replicated metadata={{op_name="e"}, {op_name="f"}}}

Metadata on tuple sharding is unsupported in favor of metadata on tuple elements.

Change-Id: I4333e5fed8740b6d684d2707953b25824e97c15a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/8f9ba797cc9ac8d5c312a5ed01a9ca398983889a"},{"sha":"6ae54f7c588862a3b9bf4eae09c3d61656716ea6","author":{"name":"RJ Skerry-Ryan","email":"7321bede801461fe8d8f2847fae8877917fad9a9@google.com"},"message":"Do not cache variable scopes in legacy_tf_layers.base.Layer when Eager is enabled (regardless of the current context).

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

Starting with ROCm 4.?, which introduces targetID support, that value will no longer be sufficient to create a LLVM AMDGPUTarget that accurately represents underlying GPU. We will need to information contained withing the `string hipDeviceProp_t gcnArchName` field for that purpose.

[{"sha":"eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Build stable and experimental with same command (#20573)

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"}]

Caching the variable scope causes the layer to be "poisoned" when used within a tf.function, since if the layer is called for the first time inside a tf.function, then a FuncGraph scope is captured and then re-entered on every subsequent call. This caching was simply a graph-building (Python) performance optimization and can be skipped if Eager is enabled.

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
